In [ ]:
# Query Twitter's API for JSON data for each tweet ID in the Twitter archive
# Reference: 'twitter-api.py' file provided in course material,  and 
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/28384588/twitter-api-get-tweets-with-specific-id and
# https://wiki.python.org/moin/HandlingExceptions and
# # https://stackoverflow.com/questions/7370801/measure-time-elapsed-in-python
count = 0
fails_dict = {}
start = time.time()
# Save each tweet's returned JSON as a new line in a .txt file
with open('tweet_json.txt', 'w') as outfile:
    for tweet_id in tweet_ids:
        count += 1
        print(str(count) + ": " + str(tweet_id))
        try:
            tweet = api.get_status(tweet_id, tweet_mode='extended')
            print("Success")
            json.dump(tweet._json, outfile)
            outfile.write('\n')
        # Tweet IDs that could not be found (deleted tweets)
        except tweepy.TweepError as e:
            print("Fail")
            fails_dict[tweet_id] = e
            pass
end = time.time()
print(end - start)
print("Number of tweet IDs that could not be found:", len(fails_dict))
print("Tweet IDs that could not be found:", fails_dict)

# Reference: https://thispointer.com/python-pandas-how-to-add-rows-in-a-dataframe-using-dataframe-append-loc-iloc/ and
# https://stackabuse.com/reading-and-writing-json-to-a-file-in-python/
with open('tweet_json.txt') as file:
    # Create pandas dataframe with relevant columns
    tweets_json = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['tweet_id',
                                        'retweet_count',
                                        'favorite_count',
                                        'followers_count'])
    for line in file:
        # Parse file line by line (per tweet)
        tweet = json.loads(line)
        # Use parser to map data to dataframe columns
        tweets_json = tweets_json.append({
            'tweet_id': tweet['id'],
            'retweet_count': tweet['retweet_count'],
            'favorite_count': tweet['favorite_count'],
            'followers_count': tweet['user']['followers_count']
        }, ignore_index = True)
        
tweets_json.info()

Quality¶

  • The tables have different numbers of unique tweets (tweet_id): twitter_archive: 2356 image_predictions: 2075 tweets_json: 2342, we only want to keep original tweets (no retweets or replies) that includes a rating and an image of a dog

twitter_archive table¶

  • Table contains 78 replies (in_reply_to_status_id) and 181 retweets (retweeted_status_id), only keep original tweets
  • in_reply_to_status_id, in_reply_to_user_id are floats and not integers and have rows with missing data, NaN values. However, these columns might not have to be included if only original tweets are present in the table
  • retweeted_status_id, retweeted_status_user_id are floats and not integers and have rows with missing data, NaN values. However, these columns might not have to be included if only original tweets are present in the table (missing data goes for retweeted_status_timestamp as well)
  • timestamp is a string and not datetime and has +0000 in text
  • source is a string and and has HTML code in it, it would probably be more useful as categorical and to only include text Twitter for iPhone, Vine - Make a Scene, Twitter Web Client, TweetDeck for each category option
  • Some tweets have the same expanded url, there are 137 duplicates of expanded_urls in the table
  • Not all rating_numerators seem to have been fetched from text correctly
  • Not all rating_denominators seem to have been fetched from text correctly
  • rating_numerator and rating_denominator are integers and not floats, there are ratings with decimals in tweet text
  • The name column seems to have faulty names, such as: a, the, an, one, O
  • Have the columns doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo been correctly fetched from the text column?
  • Columns doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo are strings and not categorical
  • Doge stage names are in lowercase in columns doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo
  • There are extra characters after & in tweet text

image_predictions table¶

  • Some tweets have the same image url, there are 66 duplicates of jpg_url in the table
  • p1, p2, p3 are objects and not categorical and some names are in lowercase with an underscore instead of a space between words
  • Not all images are of dogs, see True/False in columns p1_dog, p2_dog, p3_dog

tweets_json table¶

  • tweet_id, retweet_count, favorite_count, followers_count are strings and not integers

Tidiness¶

  • There are 3 separate tables for the same type of observational unit, image_predictions and tweets_json should be part of the twitter_archive table
  • tweet_id must be of the same data type in all tables to be able to merge these
  • One variable representing dog stage in twitter_archive table (for existing columns doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo)
  • Two variables for dog breed and confidence level in image prediction file, only containing predictions of dogs ( for existing columns: p1, p1_conf, p1_dog, p2, p2_conf, p2_dog, p3, p3_conf, p3_dog)
  • Values inp1_conf,p2_conf,p3_confwould be better expressed as whole number percentages

Clean¶

In [155]:
twitter_archive_clean = twitter_archive.copy()
image_predictions_clean = image_predictions.copy()
tweets_json_clean = tweets_json.copy()

Tidiness¶

Define¶

  • Change tweet_id to an integer in tweets_json table to be able to merge tables

Define¶

  • Replace columns p1, p1_conf, p1_dog, p2, p2_conf, p2_dog, p3, p3_conf, p3_dog with one column with dog_breed_prediction and one column with dog_breed_confidence_level, fill these with data where it is missing with prioritized order from p1 to p3, where the tweet has an image of a dog. Make dog_breed_prediction categorical and capitalize all values and replace the underscore between words in some values with a space. Convert dog_breed_confidence_level to an integer with numbers expressed as percentages.

Code¶

In [169]:
# Function that returns the first prediciton of dog breed where the prediction is a breed of dog
# Reference: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/27041724/using-conditional-to-generate-new-column-in-pandas-dataframe
def breed(twitter_archive_clean):
    if twitter_archive_clean['p1_dog'] == True:
        return twitter_archive_clean['p1']
    elif twitter_archive_clean['p2_dog'] == True:
        return twitter_archive_clean['p2']
    elif twitter_archive_clean['p3_dog'] == True:
        return twitter_archive_clean['p3']
    else:
        return 'Undefined'

# Populate a column with the dog breed data
twitter_archive_clean['dog_breed_prediction'] = twitter_archive_clean.apply(breed, axis = 1)

# Function that returns the confidence level of the first prediciton of dog breed where the prediction is a breed of dog
def confidence_level(twitter_archive_clean):
    if twitter_archive_clean['p1_dog'] == True:
        return twitter_archive_clean['p1_conf']
    elif twitter_archive_clean['p2_dog'] == True:
        return twitter_archive_clean['p2_conf']
    elif twitter_archive_clean['p3_dog'] == True:
        return twitter_archive_clean['p3_conf']
    else:
        return 0

# Populate a column with the confidence level data
twitter_archive_clean['dog_breed_confidence_level'] = twitter_archive_clean.apply(confidence_level, axis = 1)
In [170]:
# Make all dog breed values start with Capital
twitter_archive_clean['dog_breed_prediction'] = twitter_archive_clean['dog_breed_prediction'].str.capitalize()

# Replace underscore with space in dog breed values
twitter_archive_clean['dog_breed_prediction'] = twitter_archive_clean['dog_breed_prediction'].str.replace( "_", " ")

# Change dog_breed_prediction column from integer to category
twitter_archive_clean['dog_breed_prediction'] = twitter_archive_clean['dog_breed_prediction'].astype('category')
In [171]:
# Convert dog_breed_confidence_level to a two digit integer to express a percentage
twitter_archive_clean['dog_breed_confidence_level'] = round(twitter_archive_clean['dog_breed_confidence_level']*100).astype(int)
In [172]:
# Only keep new columns dog_breed_prediction and dog_breed_confidence_level
twitter_archive_clean = twitter_archive_clean.drop(['p1', 'p1_conf', 'p1_dog', 'p2', 'p2_conf', 'p2_dog', 'p3', 'p3_conf', 'p3_dog'], axis = 1)

Quality¶

Define¶

  • Remove tweets that are replies or retweets (has a value in retweeted_status_id or in_reply_to_status_id), does not have image prediction data (does not have a value in jpg_url), does not have any dog breed prediciton data ('Undefined' in dog_breed_prediction).

  • Check tweets where a dog breed has been predicted but where the conficende level of that prediction is 0. Remove tweet if prediciton is not of a dog. Also remove tweets that have been deleted (has no value in retweet_count).

Define¶

  • Check all rating_denominators with a value other than 10. Replace value with correct one from tweet text if necessary and delete tweet from dataset if the rating is not of a dog.
  • Check all rating_numerators with a value of less than 5 or more than 20. Replace value with correct one from tweet text if necessary and delete tweet from dataset if the rating is not of a dog.
  • Change both variable rating_denominator and rating_numerator into floats since there are ratings with decimals in tweet texts.

# Make rating_numerator and rating_denominator floats

Engagement Rate¶

An engagement rate is a metric that measures the level of engagement that a piece of created content is receiving from an audience. It shows how much people interact with the content. This is an important metric to keep an on eye on because higher consumer engagement is a sign of great content (source).¶

Engagement rate (%) for a tweet is here defined as the number of retweets and favorites (likes) a post has, divided by the total number of followers the account has, multiplied by 100 to get a percentage number.¶


In [227]:
# Create column with the engagement rate (%) for each tweet, where engagment is number of retweets and favorites (likes) for a post. To get the engagement rate this is divided by the total number of followers the account has, multiplied by 100 to get a percentage number
twitter_archive_clean['engagement_rate'] = (twitter_archive_clean['retweet_count'] + twitter_archive_clean['favorite_count']) / twitter_archive_clean['followers_count'] * 100
In [228]:
twitter_archive_clean['engagement_rate'].describe()
Out[228]:
count    1651.000000
mean        0.159347
std         0.241996
min         0.001229
25%         0.036678
50%         0.075853
75%         0.192925
max         3.322495
Name: engagement_rate, dtype: float64

On Twitter, an engagement rate between 0% and 0.02% is considered to be low. Engagement rates between 0.02% and 0.09% are considered to be good and an engagement rate between 0.09% and 0.33% is considered to be high (source).¶

The table above shows that the avgerage engagement rate for a tweet with an image and rating of a dog posted by WeRateDogs is 0.159%, which lies within the range that is concidered to be a high engagement rate.¶

Engagement Rate over time¶

In [242]:
# Scatter plot of engagement rate over time
# Reference: https://jakevdp.github.io/PythonDataScienceHandbook/04.02-simple-scatter-plots.html
plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 17})
plt.figure(figsize = (16, 7))
plt.plot(twitter_archive_clean['timestamp'], twitter_archive_clean['engagement_rate'], '.', color = 'black');
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Engagement Rate (%)')
plt.title('Engagement Rate over Time')
plt.show()

This scatter plot shows the engagement rate over time, one dot represents the engagement rate of one tweet. We can see that there are some extreme cases where the engagement rate is very high relative to all tweets in the dataset. The engagement rate appears to have increased slightly over time and also the variation in engagement rates have become greater, meanwhile the number of tweets have become fewer.¶

Dog Ratings¶

The rating score of a dog is calculated by dividing the rating numerator with the rating denominator. The average rating numerator of a tweet is 11.37, the average rating denominator is 10.45 and the average rating score is 1.09.¶

In [239]:
# Create column with dog rating for each tweet, where the rating is calculated by dividing the rating numerator with the rating denominator
twitter_archive_clean['dog_rating'] = (twitter_archive_clean['rating_numerator'] / twitter_archive_clean['rating_denominator'])
In [240]:
print("Average rating numerator:", twitter_archive_clean['rating_numerator'].mean())
print("Average rating denominator:", twitter_archive_clean['rating_denominator'].mean())
print("Average rating score:", twitter_archive_clean['dog_rating'].mean())

Average rating numerator: 11.367825560266505
Average rating denominator: 10.448213204118716
Average rating score: 1.0871156874621464
